article.headline: Houston 93, Washington 80
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Highlights from the Houston Rockets play-by-play, starting with nine minutes remaining in the game: layup, dunk, reverse layup, 4-foot jump shot, layup, dunk. And that was with Yao Ming on the bench. Yao scored 14 of his 21 points in the third quarter, but he wasn't needed in the decisive run in the fourth as the Rockets shredded the Washington Wizards' interior defense in Tuesday night's 93-80 victory. Cuttino Mobley, Steve Francis and Jim Jackson scored 16 points apiece, and Francis had eight rebounds and 10 of the Rockets' season-high 27 assists. Yao made 6 of 9 field goals, 9 of 10 free throws and had 11 rebounds, and the Rockets shot 52 percent. "When you make shots, that's also how you get assists," coach Jeff Van Gundy said. "Sometimes we move the ball real well, and we don't shoot particularly well. Tonight we shot well." Washington's fourth-quarter defense prompted some of the harshest words yet from coach Eddie Jordan, whose team has lost 10 of 12. Twice he said the team "didn't grow up," adding for emphasis: "We didn't play like men tonight." "We just didn't protect our paint. We didn't rotate properly," Jordan said. "We let people score at the basket. We didn't have enough pride to work header. We didn't have enough pride to protect the rim. We didn't grow up." "You need a little bit more heart," added Jordan, clearly upset but never raising his voice. "You need a little bit more trust in your teammates. You need to play intelligently, and you've got to know how to win. We don't just have a feel to win the game." One obvious target was of his remarks was Kwame Brown, who was 0-for-4 with one rebound in the fourth quarter. Asked about Brown not getting the calls on the offensive end, Jordan offered no sympathy. "You've got to make them make the call," Jordan said. "That's part of being a man in this game." Brown said he had to ease up in the fourth quarter because he had four fouls and little backup, with the Wizards having lost Christian Laettner earlier in the day to a five-game suspension for violating the NBA's drug policy. "And then a lot of the tic-tac-toe calls they gave us," Brown said. "And a guy 7-6 (Yao), they don't want us to touch him going to the basket. I don't understand that. ... Officials are not going to respect this team. They're definitely not going to respect me." Larry Hughes scored 23 points to lead the Wizards, who are also without injured scorers Gilbert Arenas and Jerry Stackhouse. Most of Yao's points came after he was leveled by Brendan Haywood midway through the third quarter. Yao lay on the floor for about 30 seconds, but he stayed in the game and made both free throws, the start of a run in which he scored 12 of his team's 19 points to end the quarter. The downside for the Rockets was their 21 turnovers. Francis had seven, giving Van Gundy a ready answer when asked about Francis being only two rebounds from a triple-double. "And three turnovers shy of a quadruple-double. That would've been very special," Van Gundy said. "Yes, he did a good job. He had many implosions with the ball, but other than that he shot a high percentage and made good plays for everybody."

Game notes
Van Gundy wouldn't give a straight answer when asked about a report that the Rockets are planning to work out former All-Star guard Mark Jackson. "Is there talk about that? I didn't realize that," the coach said. ... Houston's reserves shot 0-for-5 in the first half. ... The Rockets are 7-2 on the road against Eastern Conference teams.
